[[File:EspioOnCeiling.JPG|thumb|left|Espio runs on the ceiling in a level of ''Knuckles' Chaotix'', with Charmy as his partner. Partners in the game are joined by "Ring Power".|alt=The chameleon runs on an unsupported ceiling in a colorful two-dimensional game level. An anthropomorphic bee standing on a large floating platform is attached to him via a long chain that each character holds an end of.]]
Espio debuted in ''Knuckles' Chaotix'' as a [[player character]] alongside the rest of the Chaotix<U+2014>a team which included [[Mighty the Armadillo]] in this game<U+2014>as well as [[Knuckles the Echidna]] and two robots named Heavy and Bomb.<ref name="ign kc"/> The premise involves [[Doctor Ivo Robotnik|Doctor Eggman]] using power from the [[Sonic the Hedgehog (series)#Chaos Emeralds|Chaos Emerald]] that powers the "Carnival Island" amusement park in order to power his own "Combi Confiner" machine. Knuckles, who patrols the island, finds that Eggman has captured the Chaotix. Once Espio is rescued, he joins with Knuckles to defeat Eggman.

Espio is playable in the [[arcade game|arcade]] [[fighting game]] ''[[Sonic the Fighters]]'', later ported to the [[Nintendo GameCube]] and [[PlayStation 2]] as part of ''[[Sonic Gems Collection]]''.<ref name="fighters"/> Four of his attacking moves make use of his tongue, a feature not demonstrated elsewhere in the series.<ref>''Sonic Gems Collection'' (GameCube), instruction booklet, p. 13.</ref>

The Chaotix is one of four playable three-player teams in ''Sonic Heroes''.<ref name="profiles"/> The team receives a package in the mail which contains a [[walkie-talkie]] through which an unknown client requests the team's help, promising to "pay handsomely". Espio is suspicious, but Vector and Charmy focus on the opportunity to make money, to which Espio consents.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Sonic Heroes]]|developer=[[Sonic Team#Sega Studio USA (Sonic Team USA)|Sega Studio USA]]|quote='''Charmy:''' It's here, it's here... we've got work! / '''Vector:''' WHAT? (The package opens, and a walkie-talkie falls out) / '''Voice:''' I've heard good things about you and require your detective services. And I can pay handsomely. (Vector's and Charmy's eyes appear as dollar signs for a second, then revert to normal) / '''Espio:''' I've got a bad feeling about this... / '''Vector:''' Espio, don't be silly! Besides, you know our policy. We never turn down work that pays! / '''Charmy:''' Yeah, you know our policy! / '''Vector:''' C'mon boys, let's go! / '''Espio:''' Roger.}}</ref> As the quest progresses, Espio begins to suspect that the owner of the voice is a relative of Doctor Eggman, a sentiment which Vector deems feasible.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Heroes|developer=Sega Studio USA|quote='''Espio:''' Definitely an agent... a relative, perhaps. / '''Vector:''' Strangely enough, I had the same weird feeling about our clients' {{sic}} REAL identity.}}</ref> When the client is revealed to be Eggman himself, the team is disappointed at their own incompetence. Eggman then reveals that he plans to [[world domination|conquer the world]] before paying them, which leads to Charmy beating him up.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Sonic Heroes|developer=Sega Studio USA|quote='''Vector:''' We're here to save you. (pounds on door, then breaks it down) Dr. Eggman, I presume. / (Eggman, initially lying down, gets up) '''Espio:''' What's going on? / '''Charmy:''' What's up? / '''Eggman:''' You knew it was me all along, didn't you. / '''Vector:''' It's all part of being a good detective. / '''Espio:''' Were we fooled that easily? / '''Charmy:''' You're ROTTEN! / '''Eggman:''' Hey hold on you guys! It's no trick and besides I plan on paying you. You'll be rewarded handsomely for helping me! As soon as I conquer the world, I will pay you! / '''Vector:''' Some nerve promising what you ain't got! / '''Espio:''' We've been had! / '''Eggman:''' It's just... wait a minute, just listen to me! / '''Charmy:''' Take this you BAD MAN! (proceeds to beat Eggman up) / '''Eggman:''' Whaaaaaaaa! Aaaaahhhhh!!}}</ref>

In a "Hero"-type mission in ''[[Shadow the Hedgehog (video game)|Shadow the Hedgehog]]'', Espio requests [[Shadow the Hedgehog]]'s help in extracting data from Eggman's computer database.<ref>{{cite video game|title=[[Shadow the Hedgehog (video game)|Shadow the Hedgehog]]|developer=Sega Studio USA|quote='''Espio:''' Shadow, thanks for your help earlier. Actually, I need to extract some data from Eggman's database. Feel like lending me a hand?}}</ref> Shadow, the only player character in the game, can choose to accept or ignore Espio's request.

Espio is one of eight playable racers in the [[PlayStation Portable]] [[racing video game|racing game]] ''[[Sonic Rivals 2]]''.<ref name="hedgehog">{{cite web|title=Sonic Rivals 2 Review|url=http://psp.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r32851.htm|publisher=[[GameZone]]|date=November 26, 2007|accessdate=May 3, 2010}}</ref> Espio works with [[Silver the Hedgehog]] to find out what happened to the missing [[Chao (Sonic the Hedgehog)|Chao]] creatures.

Espio appears in ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Games]]'' and ''[[Mario & Sonic at the Olympic Winter Games]]'' as a referee, and also as a costume that the player's [[Mii]] can wear in the latter.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mario and Sonic at the Olympic Games characters list|url=http://www.videogamesblogger.com/2009/10/11/mario-and-sonic-at-the-olympic-winter-games-characters-list.htm|publisher=Video Games Blogger|date=October 11, 2009|accessdate=May 27, 2010}}</ref>

===In the comics===
In the ''[[Sonic the Comic]]'' [[comic book]] series published in the United Kingdom by [[Fleetway Editions]], Espio attempts to ambush Knuckles<U+2014>who thinks the Chaotix are crazy<U+2014>but fails.<ref>{{cite comic|title=[[Sonic the Comic]]|issue=54|date=June 23, 1995|publisher=[[Fleetway Editions]]}}</ref>

Espio is a recurring character in the United States series ''[[Sonic the Hedgehog (comics)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]'' published by [[Archie Comics]]. He grew up as a member of the "[[Shinobi]] Clan" of the "Dragon Kingdom" region. He later departed to join the community of the "Rainbow Valley" region of "Floating Island". Espio met Vector, Charmy, and Mighty when Knuckles requested their help to defeat [[Metal Sonic]]. The group eventually became friends, and the Chaotix team was formed. In the ''Mobius: X Years Later'' canon of the same series, Espio works as Knuckles's secretary, and has two daughters named Salma and Juanita.<ref>{{cite comic|title=[[Sonic the Hedgehog (comics)|Sonic the Hedgehog]]|issue=131|date=December 2003|publisher=[[Archie Comics]]}}</ref>

===In the anime===
Espio was a minor recurring character in the ''[[Sonic X]]'' [[anime]] that ran from 2003 to 2006. He initially appears along with Vector and Charmy to look for [[Cream the Rabbit]], confronting [[Miles "Tails" Prower]] and [[Amy Rose]] in the process.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Defective Detectives|episodelink=List of Sonic X episodes#Season 2: 2004-2005|series=[[Sonic X]]|airdate=December 28, 2003|season=2|number=39}}</ref> In a later episode, Vector accepts the offer of [[Vanilla the Rabbit]], Cream's mother, to look for her, but Espio mentions that they don't have a spaceship.<ref>{{cite episode|title=Galactic Gumshoes|episodelink=List of Sonic X episodes#Season 3: 2005-2006|series=Sonic X|airdate=October 22, 2005|season=3|number=59}}</ref>

==Cultural impact==
===Merchandising===
Espio has seen limited inclusion in officially released ''Sonic'' merchandise. In 1996, Espio's likeness in ''Sonic the Fighters'' was adapted into a [[plush toy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animemate.com/proddetail.php?prod=sonic-b28|publisher=AnimeMate|title=1996 Espio Sonic the Fighters Plush|accessdate=May 11, 2010}}</ref> In March 2010, Joe Amaro of plastic toy manufacturer Jazwares announced to Sega and the online community that an Espio toy was in production.<ref>{{cite web|title=Q&A with Joe Amaro from Jazwares|url=http://blogs.sega.com/sonic/2010/03/12/|date=March 12, 2010|publisher=Sega|accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref>

===Critical reception===
Espio has been generally well-received by critics. ''[[Mega Zone]]''{{'}}s review of ''Knuckles' Chaotix'' stated that the introduction of Espio, along with Charmy, provided variety in the cast and could "keep you amused for many a night."<ref>{{cite journal|title=Chaotix: 32X Review|journal=[[Mega Zone]]|date=April 1995|issue=50|page=22}}</ref> [[IGN]]'s Travis Fahs opined that "the Chaotix crew was a hoot", highlighting "aerial maneuvers" such as Espio's trademark wall-running.<ref name="ign kc">{{cite web|title=Knuckles Chaotix Review|url=http://retro.ign.com/articles/862/862183p1.html|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=March 26, 2008|last=Fahs|first=Travis|accessdate=May 28, 2010}}</ref> A preview of ''Knuckles' Chaotix'' by ''[[Sega Saturn Magazine|Sega Magazine]]'' called him "[a]nother Sonic wannabe",<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Sega Saturn Magazine|Sega Magazine]]|page=23|title=Chaotix Preview|publisher=[[EMAP]]}}</ref> a position later echoed by [[GameZone]].<ref name="hedgehog"/> ''Sega Magazine''{{'}}s second, more in-depth preview of ''Knuckles' Chaotix'' stated that "what you'll be interested in is his speed and his strange ability to stick to any surface <U+2013> and that includes running upside down. What a geezer."<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Sega Magazine|page=52|title=Who's Who in Chaotix?|publisher=EMAP}}</ref> ''[[Xbox World 360|Xbox World]]''{{'}}s preview of ''Sonic Heroes'' opined that "Espio the Chameleon isn't completely rubbish, just mostly rubbish", citing poor visual appearance in both ''Knuckles' Chaotix'' and ''Sonic Heroes''.<ref name="xboxworld">{{cite journal|journal=[[Xbox World 360|Xbox World]]|page=36|issue=2|title=Sonic Heroes}}</ref>

